    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>103</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>122500</citedRange></bibl>.
                Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#cassels1955"/>, p. <citedRange>29</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Εὐκλῆς">Εὐκλεῦς</name></persName></persName>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> fils (ou fille) d'Euklès</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> son (or daughter) of Eukles.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> figlio (o figlia) di Eukles.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>Cassels in his 1955 publication only mentioned the presence of inscriptions. From his archive, the Thorns were able to recover a copy and a large 
               scale photograph, which does not help much. They also were able to check the layout and reading of this inscription and of two others from the same tomb 
               (see <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr122600</ref> and <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr122700</ref>).</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
